Hand calculate the (unadjusted) \(R^2\) and adjusted \(R^2\). Analyse the result of the model fit and report your conclusions.

# Calculate the R squared 
calcium_data<- data.frame(calcium_regression, y_hat = fitted(calcium), e = residuals(calcium))
rss <- sum((calcium_data$metabolite-calcium_data$y_hat) ^ 2)  ## residual sum of squares
tss <- sum((calcium_data$metabolite - mean(calcium_data$metabolite)) ^ 2)  ## total sum of squares
rsq <- 1 - rss/tss
rsq
## [1] 0.7798344
# Calculate the adjusted R squared
arsq <- 1- ((1-rsq)*(11-1)/(11-1-1))
arsq
## [1] 0.7553716

R-squared is a statistical measure of how close the data are to the fitted regression line.It is also known as the coefficient of determination

Adjusted r squared is more useful when we have more than 1 independent variables since it adjusts the r square and takes only into consideration the relevant independent variable, which actually explains the variation in the dependent variable. Its value is always less than the R2 value

Therefore, based on the explaination above, we can not simply judge the model with only R-squared value. However, the R-squared value in this specific case do show a approximately 70% of the observed variation can be explained by the model’s inputs.

(c)

In a manual, step-wise manner (up to a point), in each round of model simplification, remove the explanatory variable with the highest p-value and report on the p-values of the remaining explanatory variables in the simpler model.

There is a formal way of checking whether the simplification was justified that is based on an F statistic computed form the residuals of the 2 models being compared. The R function is anova(), and the arguments are the 2 model names, with the simpler model first. For example, if one were to compare the full model with the one after removing explanatory variable 3, the command would be anova(lm1245,lm12345). The output includes the p-value for an F statistic for the null hypothesis that there is no difference in the explanatory power between the 2 models. A p-value higher than some cutoff, e.g., 0.01, indicates that the simplification was justified.

Continue the simplification process and check to see if the justification was justified for each round of model simplification, until reaching a point where no further simplification is justified. Report your final model and the p-values of the regression coefficients.

Slightly not the same, if we consider the cutoff should less than 0.05. While comparing lm4 and lm45, the X5 gives a p-value of 0.05642 It is not significant if the cutoff is less than 0.05. However, the step function still gives the X5 in the final model. The reason is that the aim of stepAIC is to give you the model with the lowest AIC. The model lm45 indeed has a lower AIC value compared with lm4.
